  "analysis": "The OCaml build segfaults early when boot/ocamlc is run, indicating a runtime GC issue. The change described (run-length compressed free space in the major heap) affects how free blocks are represented and linked. We inspected runtime/shared_heap.c and saw that free runs are encoded with headers using Wosize_hp(p) for the number of additional contiguous free blocks and the second word p[1] as a pointer to the next non-contiguous free run head. Allocation logic (pool_allocate) depends on p[1] being correctly initialized. Our grep shows sweeping logic around lines 590–656: when a block becomes free, its header is set to POOL_FREE_HEADER(0), and free runs are merged if contiguous, otherwise the previous run head's [1] is set to point to the new head; at the end, last_free_block[1] is set to 0. This is promising, but we need to open the full context to verify that next_obj is initialized for pools and that p[1] is always set correctly. The persistent segfault suggests a corner case where r->next_obj or p[1] remains uninitialized (e.g., no free blocks in a pool, or first free run head not linked yet). We'll inspect the specific code regions to confirm and apply a fix, then rebuild.",
